Stepped-Wedge Analysis Examples

February 12, 2025

library(swCRTdesign)     # Generate data from stepped-wedge designs
library(data.table)      # Data tables and manipulation
library(glmmTMB)         # Generalized Linear Mixed-Effects
library(tidyverse)       # For ggplot, dplyr, and friends
library(broom)           # Convert model objects into data frames
library(broom.mixed)     # broom for mixed-effects models
library(Statamarkdown)   # Call Stata within R
library(fixest)
library(did)
# Kennedy-Shaffer et al. 2019 Analysis Methods
source("ackcom5_sw-crt analysis methods.r")

Voldal, E. C., Hakhu, N. R., Xia, F., Heagerty, P. J., & Hughes, J. P. (2020). swCRTdesign: an R Package for stepped wedge trial design and analysis. Computer methods and programs in biomedicine, 196, 105514.

design <- swDsn(clusters=c(4,4,4,4,4,4))

set.seed(8277889)

DT <- swSim(design, family=binomial(link="logit"), n=350, 
            mu0=qlogis(0.45), 
            mu1=log(2) + qlogis(0.45), 
            time.effect=0, tau=0.2, eta=0,
            rho=0, gamma=0, time.lab=seq(0,6,1))

setDT(DT)

DT[, tx.fact := factor(tx.var, labels = c("Control","Treatment"))]
DT[, time.fact := factor(time.var, levels = c("0","1","2","3","4","5","6"))]
DT <- merge(DT[tx.var == 1, .(first_treat = min(time.var)), by = .(cluster.var)],
            DT, all = TRUE, by = "cluster.var")

DT[, Indexes := cluster.var*max(time.var)+time.var]

DT[, clustime := interaction(cluster.var, time.fact)]
  • True odds ratio is 2.0
  • True risk difference is 0.17 (0.45 vs.Â 0.62)
swSummary(response.var = response.var, tx.var = tx.fact, 
          time.var = time.fact, cluster.var = cluster.var, data = DT)

Visual Exploratory Data Analysis

ggplot(DT[, .(Mean = mean(response.var)), by = .(time.fact, tx.fact, cluster.var)], 
       aes(x = time.fact, y = Mean, color = tx.fact)) +
  geom_jitter(width=0.04, alpha=1/2) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits=c(0,1)) +
  labs(x = "Period", y = "Outcome Probability", color = "") +
  theme_minimal()

Analysis in R

Hussey & Hughes Mixed-Effects Regression Model

Hussey, M. A., & Hughes, J. P. (2007). Design and analysis of stepped wedge cluster randomized trials. Contemporary clinical trials, 28(2), 182-191.

fm1 <- glmmTMB(response.var ~ tx.fact + time.fact + (1 | cluster.var), 
        data = DT, family = binomial)

Other mixed-effects regression models

design <- swDsn(clusters=c(4,4,4,4,4,4))

set.seed(853294)

DT <- swSim(design, family=binomial(link="logit"), n=350, 
            mu0=qlogis(0.45), 
            mu1=log(2) + qlogis(0.45), 
            time.effect=0, tau=0.2, eta=0,
            rho=0, gamma=0.2, time.lab=seq(0,6,1))

setDT(DT)

DT[, tx.fact := factor(tx.var, labels = c("Control","Treatment"))]
DT[, time.fact := factor(time.var, levels = c("0","1","2","3","4","5","6"))]
DT <- merge(DT[tx.var == 1, .(first_treat = min(time.var)), by = .(cluster.var)],
            DT, all = TRUE, by = "cluster.var")

DT[, Indexes := cluster.var*max(time.var)+time.var]

DT[, clustime := interaction(cluster.var, time.fact)]
  • True odds ratio is 2.0
  • True risk difference is 0.17 (0.45 vs.Â 0.62)
  • Time effect standard deviation (across sites) of 0.20

pred_DT <- merge(data.frame(tx.fact = factor(c("Control","Treatment"))),
                 unique(DT[,.(cluster.var,time.fact,Indexes)]), all = TRUE)

pred_DT$LOGIT <- predict(fm4, newdata = pred_DT)

setDT(pred_DT)

pred_DT[, Month := as.numeric(as.character(time.fact))]

pred_DT <- pred_DT[order(cluster.var, tx.fact, Month),]

ggplot(pred_DT, aes(x=Month, y = LOGIT, color = tx.fact)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_path() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0,6,1)) +
  labs(x = "Period", y = "Outcome log Odds") +
  facet_wrap(~ cluster.var, ncol=6) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Random effect for treatment (each cluster has a deviation around an average treatment effect)

design <- swDsn(clusters=c(4,4,4,4,4,4))

set.seed(1545954)

DT <- swSim(design, family=binomial(link="logit"), n=350, 
            mu0=qlogis(0.45), 
            mu1=log(2) + qlogis(0.45), 
            time.effect=0, tau=0.2, eta=0.25,
            rho=0, gamma=0, time.lab=seq(0,6,1))

setDT(DT)

DT[, tx.fact := factor(tx.var, labels = c("Control","Treatment"))]
DT[, time.fact := factor(time.var, levels = c("0","1","2","3","4","5","6"))]
DT <- merge(DT[tx.var == 1, .(first_treat = min(time.var)), by = .(cluster.var)],
            DT, all = TRUE, by = "cluster.var")

DT[, Indexes := cluster.var*max(time.var)+time.var]

DT[, clustime := interaction(cluster.var, time.fact)]
  • True odds ratio is 2.0
  • True risk difference is 0.17 (0.45 vs.Â 0.62)
  • Treatment effect standard deviation (across sites) of 0.25

            mu0=qlogis(0.45), 
            mu1=log(2) + qlogis(0.45), 
            time.effect=0, tau=0.2, eta=0.25,
            rho=0, gamma=0.2, time.lab=seq(0,6,1))

            DT, all = TRUE, by = "cluster.var")

DT[, Indexes := cluster.var*max(time.var)+time.var]

DT[, clustime := interaction(cluster.var, time.fact)]

Permutation Test for Treatment Effect

Thompson, J. A., Davey, C., Fielding, K., Hargreaves, J. R., & Hayes, R. J. (2018). Robust analysis of stepped wedge trials using clusterâlevel summaries within periods. Statistics in Medicine, 37(16), 2487-2500.

Thompson, J., Davey, C., Hayes, R., Hargreaves, J., & Fielding, K. (2019). Permutation tests for stepped-wedge cluster-randomized trials. The Stata Journal, 19(4), 803-819.

KennedyâShaffer, L., De Gruttola, V., & Lipsitch, M. (2020). Novel methods for the analysis of stepped wedge cluster randomized trials. Statistics in Medicine, 39(7), 815-844.

# From supplementary material for Thompson et al., 2018

cluster.summary <- function(data, cluster, group, time, rx, summary, null) {

  f.effect <- function(x){

    #Aggregate data by time and intervention condition
    slices.long <- aggregate(summary ~ time + rx, data = x,
                             FUN = function(X) c(mean = mean(X, na.rm = TRUE),
                                                 n = sum(!is.na(X)),
                                                 var = var(X, na.rm = TRUE)))

    slices.long$mean <- slices.long$summary[,1]
    slices.long$n <- slices.long$summary[,2]
    slices.long$var <- slices.long$summary[,3]

    #reshape so one row per time slice
    slices <- reshape(direction = "wide",
                      data = slices.long[,c("time", "rx", "mean", "n", "var")],
                      v.names = c("mean", "n", "var"),
                      idvar = c("time"),
                      timevar = "rx")

    #calculate difference
    slices$diff <- slices$mean.1 - slices$mean.0

    #Calculate a weight assuming the same variance in both arms

    slices$wgt <- ( (((slices$n.0 - 1) * slices$var.0 + (slices$n.1 - 1) * slices$var.1) /
                       (slices$n.0 + slices$n.1 - 2)) * (1/slices$n.0 + 1/slices$n.1) )^-1

    weighted.mean(slices$diff, slices$wgt, na.rm = TRUE)
  }

  f.permute <- function(y, design) {

    design$cluster <- sample(design$cluster, replace = FALSE)

    design.long <- reshape(design,
                           direction = "long",
                           idvar = c("cluster", "group"))

    permuted.data <- merge(y[, c("cluster", "time", "summary")],
                           design.long,
                           by = c("cluster", "time"))

    return(f.effect(permuted.data))
  }

  dataset <- data.frame(cluster = eval(substitute(cluster), data),
                        group = eval(substitute(group), data),
                        time = eval(substitute(time), data),
                        rx = as.numeric(eval(substitute(rx),data)),
                        summary = eval(substitute(summary),data))


  dataset$summary <- dataset$summary - null * dataset$rx


  #Calculate observed effect
  mean.effect <- f.effect(dataset)

  #Create a dataset of the design
  design <- reshape(direction = "wide",
                    idvar = c("cluster", "group"),
                    timevar = "time",
                    v.names = "rx",
                    data = unique(dataset[,c("cluster","group","rx","time")]))

  #Calculate p value under null = 0
  permutations <- replicate(100, f.permute(dataset, design), simplify = TRUE)

  p <- sum(abs(permutations) > abs(mean.effect)) / 100



  return(c(mean.effect, p))

}
cluster.summary(data = DT, 
                cluster = DT$cluster.var, 
                group = DT$first_treat, 
                time = DT$time.var, 
                rx = DT$tx.var, 
                summary = DT$response.var, 
                null = 0)

Permutation Test for Treatment Effect

use "swtDT.dta"

* Run a within-period analysis on cluster-period-level outcomes to calculate a risk difference

swpermute r(mu_2) - r(mu_1), intervention(tx_var) period(time_fact) ///
  cluster(cluster_var) withinperiod weightperiod(variance r(se)^2) ///
  reps(100): ttest response_var, by(tx_var)
